ique contribution to the study of language policy and education for English Learners because it focuses on the decade long implementation of “English Only” in Arizona. How this policy influences teacher preparation and classroom practice is the central topic of this volume. Scholars and researchers present their latest findings and concerns regarding the impact that a restrictive language policy has on critical areas for English Learners and diverse students. If a student's language is sanctioned, do they feel welcome in the classroom? If teachers are only taught about subtractive language policy, will they be able to be tolerant of linguistic diversity in their classrooms? The implications of the chapters suggest that Arizona's version of Structured English Immersion may actually limit English Learners' access to English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducation, BilingualxArizona. 0aEducation, BilingualzArizona. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakersxArizonaxArizona. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxImmersion method. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingzArizonaxForeign speakers. 0aLanguage policyxArizona. 0aLanguage policyzArizona. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh  aStructured English Immersion.  alanguage education.  alanguage policy.  amonolingualism.1 aAdamson, H. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArias, M. Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArias, M. Beatriz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCombs, Mary Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstrella-Silva, Alexandria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaltis, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://i